text: Rules for a good horror movie, by me. lol Atmosphere Good Acting Crazy/psychotic children Old skinny wrinkly women¬† whispering sounds Dark corners/closets/hallways/parkinglots/attics are great/downstairs slow dramatic ghost limbs touching others this is a really good one i enjoyed in the "eye" - slowly move antagonist towards protagonist, while the protagonists doesn't know and or is too afraid to look flickering lights, dim scenes no teens, horrors about teens always have the 1 douche constantly making jokes about stuff, ruining the atmosphere babies staring at invisible ghosts adults cannot see slow, loud knocks on door, and fastening the pace as it goes on idk if this is a real word or not, but!!! suttlely, subtly ?idk ! place the antagonist in the background, then nothing happens. lol that works! make up over cgi! A old woman with snow white skin and big pupils will always be scarier then a giant horned demon. always.¬† Of course, this comment is wrapped around the supernatural horrors, why ? it's because, let's face it, slashers/aliens are not "scary," or at least not to me. text: MY REVIEW: This trailer captivates you right from the start as if a new angel to horror was coming. Not exactly, this film is entertaining and the choice of time period is very unclear do to it's high tech smart girl make-up type thing, phone, I'm not sure. I don't even know what to make of that inning-of-itself, but the movie itself ALMOST was on to something ! It was like the ring meets the grudge meets 1 missed call among many other similar concept movies. It had a small time charm to it, the ending well lets just say it left you nothing to talk about or to feel. I felt after it ended, warm inside and calm, as if I was just dreaming this crap up (NOT literately calling/saying it crap aka bad). I did enjoy the style of the film, the shots, the angels and settings designed. The only thing this has me interested in, was the origins of this demon; is there a real myth of such a thing, so far no, seems no origin exists other then creative writing. I'm not hating this movie, I didn't love it either, it was more of that old school thrill you'd get hanging out with your friends at night watching horror flix in the woodsy backyard with a projector and fire pit just for fun. I give it a 6 of 10

text: Best horror I've seen in years. It's ambiguity makes it very unsettling and I love the directors nuances throughout the film which subconsciously makes u feel weird like something is off; like the fact that there's no established time period- they're watching black and white films on old TVs yet the friend has a clam-compact e-reader thing. There's a mixture of vintage and modern cars and the clothes and houses look old. Also [spoiler alert] she wouldn't tell her sister who she saw at the pool, because it was their dad who passed away. I know because the ghost thing looked like one of the family photographs from the house, and their mum was always day drinking in scenes, a sign of trauma. The ending is up to interpretation as is the boat scene and prostitution scene. The film doesn't have to shout the answers in your face, but rather leaves you guessing.
